{"title_page": "St Blazey", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{infobox UK place|\n|country =                 England\n|map_type=                 Cornwall\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.361|-4.716|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name = Station Road, St. Blazey, Cornwall - geograph.org.uk - 1249843.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Station Road, St. Blazey\n|official_name=            St Blazey\n|cornish_name=             Lanndreth\n|population=               6799\n|population_ref=           ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|Civil Parish, 2011]])\n|civil_parish=             St Blaise\n|unitary_england=          [[Cornwall Council|Cornwall]]\n|lieutenancy_england =     [[Cornwall]]\n|region=                   South West England\n|constituency_westminster= [[South East Cornwall (UK Parliament constituency)|South East Cornwall]]\n|post_town=                PAR\n|postcode_district =       PL24\n|postcode_area=            PL\n|dial_code=                01726 \n|os_grid_reference=        SX069548\n}}\n[[File:Church of St. Blaise, St. Blazey, Cornwall - geograph.org.uk - 1236202.jpg|thumb|Church of St. Blaise]]\n'''St Blazey''' ({{lang-kw|Lanndreth}}) is a small town in [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom.\n\n'''St Blaise''' is the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in which St Blazey is situated; the name St Blaise is also used by the town council. The village of  [[Biscovey]] and the settlements of [[St Blazey Gate]], [[Bodelva]] and West [[Par, Cornwall|Par]] lie within the parish boundaries.<ref name=cccsbtc>{{cite web | title = Cornwall Council interactive mapping website | url = http://mapping.cornwall.gov.uk/website/ccmap/ | publisher = [[Cornwall County Council]] | accessdate = 5 February 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100505124940/http://mapping.cornwall.gov.uk/website/ccmap/ | archivedate = 5 May 2010 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> An electoral ward also exists in the name of St Blaise. The population at the 2011 census was 4,674.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/st-blaise-e05008285#sthash.6ycoZxSp.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate= 12 February 2015}}</ref>\nOnce an important engineering centre for the local mine and railway industries, the parish is now dominated by the [[Eden Project]].\n\nSt Blazey is situated {{convert|3|mi|km}} east of [[St Austell]], {{convert|1|mi|km}} west of [[Tywardreath]] and {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of [[Par, Cornwall|Par]].<ref name=\"osexp1\">Ordnance Survey (2005). ''OS Explorer Map 107 \u2013 St Austell & Liskeard: Fowey, Looe & Lostwithiel''. {{ISBN|978-0-319-23708-3}}.</ref>\n\nThe town takes its name from the [[Armenians|Armenian]] [[Saint Blaise]] and holds a procession and service on his feast day, 3 February.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books/reader?id=iIUvAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&output=reader&source=gbs_atb_hover&pg=GBS.PA52|title= The Parochial History of Cornwall, Volume I |\nfirst1 = Davies| last1 =  Gilbert | first2=William | last2=Hals | first3=Thomas | last3=Tonkin | first4=Henry Samuel | last4=Boase | year= 1838 | accessdate =4 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe namesake and [[patron hallow]] of St Blazey is [[Saint Blaise]], who in high church Christianity, is believed to have \"cure[d] toothache, sore throats and cattle diseases\".<ref name=\"DeaneShaw2009\">{{cite book|last1=Deane|first1=Tony|last2=Shaw|first2=Tony|title=Folklore of Cornwall|date=1 March 2009|publisher=History Press|language=English|isbn=9780750956529|page=151}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Iron Age]] hillfort [[Prideaux Castle]] lies a mile to the north west of the town in the parish of [[Luxulyan]].<ref name=\"TownCouncil\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stblaisetowncouncil.co.uk/history.html | title=A history of St Blazey | publisher=St Blazey Town Council | accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Biscovey Stone is the shaft of an ancient [[Celts|Celtic]] cross. It was inscribed, but the text is no longer readable. There are several theories about the stone; one says it dates from around 600 AD to show the [[Saxon]] advance into the county, another puts the date at around 900 AD. The head is thought to have been removed during the [[Reformation]]. The stone served as a gate post near the St Blazey turnpike gate. In 1896 it was moved to St Mary's Church, Biscovey.<ref name=\"TownCouncil\"/> Arthur Langdon described the stone in 1896: he read the inscription as \"+ Alroron Ullici + filius\". It was also described by [[William Borlase]] in his ''Antiquities of Cornwall'' (1754), pp.&nbsp;363\u201364.<ref>Langdon, A. G. (1896) ''Old Cornish Crosses''. Truro: Joseph Pollard' pp. 368-72</ref>\n\nThe church was built between 1440 and 1445 and is dedicated to Saint Blaise. It replaces an earlier church mentioned in 1294. The parish was administered by [[Tywardreath#Tywardreath Priory|Tywardreath Priory]] until the Reformation. It was split from St Austell parish in 1834.<ref name=\"CISI\"/> The site was originally known by the Cornish names Landrait or Landreath, meaning Church on the Sand.<ref name=\"CISI\"/> A stone Gothic Latin cross stands in the churchyard but nothing is known about its history.<ref>Langdon, A. G. (2002) ''Stone Crosses in Mid Cornwall''; 2nd ed. Federation of Old Cornwall Societies; p. 23</ref>\n\nUntil the 16th century the valley below St Blazey was an estuary of the [[River Par (UK)|River Par]] and St Blazey was the [[lowest crossing point]] on the river. [[Mining in Cornwall and Devon|Tin mining]] up river caused the estuary to silt up and it had become marsh land by the early 19th century. The [[Par Canal]] was built by [[Joseph Treffry]] between 1829 and 1835; it forms part of the boundary with the parish of [[Tywardreath and Par]].<ref name=\"CISI\">{{cite web | url=http://www.historic-cornwall.org.uk/cisi/st_blazey/cisi_st_blazey_report.pdf | title=Cornwall Industrial Settlements Initiative, ST BLAZEY (with St Blazey Gate and West Par) | date=June 1999 | publisher = Historic Environment Service, Cornwall County Council | accessdate =4 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe town was once dominated by the local mining industries and their associated transport infrastructure. Historically copper and [[tin]] were mined in and around the parish, whilst more recently [[kaolinite|china clay]] has been the principal commodity mined. \"The Par & St Blazey Consols\" or \"South Prideaux Wood\" was a small tin mine just north of the town<ref>{{cite web| title=St. Austell Mining District \u2013 Par & St Blazey Consols| work=Cornwall in Focus| url=http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/blazeycons.php| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202165547/http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/blazeycons.php| archivedate=2 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Par Consols Mine]] lies to the south west.<ref>{{cite web| title=St. Austell Mining District \u2013 Par Consols Mine| work=Cornwall in Focus| url=http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/parcons.php| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202191931/http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/parcons.php| archivedate=2 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The more extensive [[Fowey Consols mine]] lies to the east near [[Tywardreath]].\n\nThe port of [[Par Harbour]], which lies within the parish, was developed to ease the transport of these minerals, and initially connected to the mines by the [[Par Canal]]. Whilst the port of Par is within the parish, the village of [[Par, Cornwall|Par]] is actually just across the [[River Par (UK)|River Par]], and hence lies in the civil parish of Tywardreath.<ref name=\"osexp1\"/>\n\nThe Par Canal was soon replaced by the [[Cornwall Minerals Railway]], which had a depot and station in the town, and still exists as part of the [[Atlantic Coast Line, Cornwall|Atlantic Coast Line]]. Whilst [[St Blazey engine shed|St Blazey depot]] is still in use, [[St Blazey railway station|St Blazey station]] closed to passengers in 1925, and the town is now served by [[Par railway station|Par station]] on the [[Cornish Main Line]] in Par village.<ref name=\"osexp1\"/>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Eden Project geodesic domes panorama.jpg|thumb|360px|Panoramic view of the geodesic biome domes at the Eden Project]]\nThe [[Eden Project]] is located within the civil parish, and about a mile and half (2&nbsp;km) from the centre of the town. The large number of visitors this attracts has led to the development of tourism in the town. Other attractions, such as the [[Treffry Viaduct]] and the [[Luxulyan Valley]], are also close by, although actually within the adjoining parish of [[Luxulyan]].<ref name=\"osexp1\"/>\n\n==Education==\nPrimary education is provided by Biscovey Nursery and Infant Community School and Biscovey Junior School.\n\n==Sport==\nThe town's football team, [[St Blazey A.F.C.]], was the first club of England International goalkeeper [[Nigel Martyn]].\n\nThe town is also home to St Blazey Cricket Club which has two teams.\nThe cricket club is based at the top of Middleway Road.\n\n==Notable people==\nNotable people from the town include [[Edward Long]], the historian, who was born at Roselyon, in 1734, and educated at [[Liskeard]]. It is claimed by some as the birthplace of [[Ralph Allen]],<ref>{{cite web| title =Ralph Allen Biography| publisher =Bath Postal Museum| url =http://www.bathpostalmuseum.co.uk/explore/biographies/ralphallen.html| accessdate =17 September 2008| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090607024648/http://www.bathpostalmuseum.co.uk/explore/biographies/ralphallen.html| archivedate =7 June 2009| df =dmy-all}}</ref> notable architect of [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], although his christening took place at [[St Columb Major]]. [[John Rogers (divine)|John Rogers]], who supported the introduction of the [[man engine]] to Cornish mines, was curate here for a time.<ref name=\"dnb\">{{cite web | last = Marchant | first = E. C. | title = Rogers, John (1778\u20131856), divine, by E. C. Marchant | work = [[Dictionary of National Biography]] Vol. IL | publisher =[[Smith, Elder & Co.]] | year = 1897 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/olddnb.jsp?articleid=23988 | accessdate =13 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Charles Jeffries]], a [[Commissioner in The Salvation Army|Commissioner]] in [[The Salvation Army]], was posted to the town in 1883.\n\n==References==\n[[File:Disused Bible Christian Chapel - geograph.org.uk - 143541.jpg|Disused Methodist (formerly Bible Christian) chapel|thumb]]\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.stblaisetowncouncil.co.uk/ Town Council website]\n* [http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/Cornwall/StBlazey/index.html GENUKI website; St Blazey]\n* [http://crocat.cornwall.gov.uk/dserve/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=Overview.tcl&dsqSearch=(((text)='st%20blazey')AND(RefNo='*')) Cornwall Record Office Online Catalogue for St Blazey]\n<!-- REMOVED LINKS THAT FAIL [[WP:ELNO]] -->\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    ======================= {{No more links}} =============================-->\n\n{{Cornwall|state=collapsed}}\n{{St Austell and Newquay CP navigation box}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Blazey}}\n[[Category:St Blazey| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cornwall]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{infobox UK place|\n|country =                 England\n|map_type=                 Cornwall\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.361|-4.716|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name = Station Road, St. Blazey, Cornwall - geograph.org.uk - 1249843.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Station Road, St. Blazey\n|official_name=            St Blazey\n|cornish_name=             Lanndreth\n|population=               6799\n|population_ref=           ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|Civil Parish, 2011]])\n|civil_parish=             St Blaise\n|unitary_england=          [[Cornwall Council|Cornwall]]\n|lieutenancy_england =     [[Cornwall]]\n|region=                   South West England\n|constituency_westminster= [[South East Cornwall (UK Parliament constituency)|South East Cornwall]]\n|post_town=                PAR\n|postcode_district =       PL24\n|postcode_area=            PL\n|dial_code=                01726 \n|os_grid_reference=        SX069548\n}}\n[[File:Church of St. Blaise, St. Blazey, Cornwall - geograph.org.uk - 1236202.jpg|thumb|Church of St. Blaise]]\n'''St Blazey''' ({{lang-kw|Lanndreth}}) is a small town in [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom.\n\n'''St Blaise''' is the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in which St Blazey is situated; the name St Blaise is also used by the town council. The village of  [[Biscovey]] and the settlements of [[St Blazey Gate]], [[Bodelva]] and West [[Par, Cornwall|Par]] lie within the parish boundaries.<ref name=cccsbtc>{{cite web | title = Cornwall Council interactive mapping website | url = http://mapping.cornwall.gov.uk/website/ccmap/ | publisher = [[Cornwall County Council]] | accessdate = 5 February 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100505124940/http://mapping.cornwall.gov.uk/website/ccmap/ | archivedate = 5 May 2010 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> An electoral ward also exists in the name of St Blaise. The population at the 2011 census was 4,674.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/st-blaise-e05008285#sthash.6ycoZxSp.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate= 12 February 2015}}</ref>\nOnce an important engineering centre for the local mine and railway industries, the parish is now dominated by the [[Eden Project]].\n\nSt Blazey is situated {{convert|3|mi|km}} east of [[St Austell]], {{convert|1|mi|km}} west of [[Tywardreath]] and {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of [[Par, Cornwall|Par]].<ref name=\"osexp1\">Ordnance Survey (2005). ''OS Explorer Map 107 \u2013 St Austell & Liskeard: Fowey, Looe & Lostwithiel''. {{ISBN|978-0-319-23708-3}}.</ref>\n\nThe town takes its name from the [[Armenians|Armenian]] [[Saint Blaise]] and holds a procession and service on his feast day, 3 February.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books/reader?id=iIUvAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&output=reader&source=gbs_atb_hover&pg=GBS.PA52|title= The Parochial History of Cornwall, Volume I |\nfirst1 = Davies| last1 =  Gilbert | first2=William | last2=Hals | first3=Thomas | last3=Tonkin | first4=Henry Samuel | last4=Boase | year= 1838 | accessdate =4 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe namesake and [[patron hallow]] of St Blazey is [[Saint Blaise]], who in high church Christianity, is believed to have \"cure[d] toothache, sore throats and cattle diseases\".<ref name=\"DeaneShaw2009\">{{cite book|last1=Deane|first1=Tony|last2=Shaw|first2=Tony|title=Folklore of Cornwall|date=1 March 2009|publisher=History Press|language=English|isbn=9780750956529|page=151}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Iron Age]] hillfort [[Prideaux Castle]] lies a mile to the north west of the town in the parish of [[Luxulyan]].<ref name=\"TownCouncil\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stblaisetowncouncil.co.uk/history.html | title=A history of St Blazey | publisher=St Blazey Town Council | accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Biscovey Stone is the shaft of an ancient [[Celts|Celtic]] cross. It was inscribed, but the text is no longer readable. There are several theories about the stone; one says it dates from around 600 AD to show the [[Saxon]] advance into the county, another puts the date at around 900 AD. The head is thought to have been removed during the [[Reformation]]. The stone served as a gate post near the St Blazey turnpike gate. In 1896 it was moved to St Mary's Church, Biscovey.<ref name=\"TownCouncil\"/> Arthur Langdon described the stone in 1896: he read the inscription as \"+ Alroron Ullici + filius\". It was also described by [[William Borlase]] in his ''Antiquities of Cornwall'' (1754), pp.&nbsp;363\u201364.<ref>Langdon, A. G. (1896) ''Old Cornish Crosses''. Truro: Joseph Pollard' pp. 368-72</ref>\n\nThe church was built between 1440 and 1445 and is dedicated to Saint Blaise. It replaces an earlier church mentioned in 1294. The parish was administered by [[Tywardreath#Tywardreath Priory|Tywardreath Priory]] until the Reformation. It was split from St Austell parish in 1834.<ref name=\"CISI\"/> The site was originally known by the Cornish names Landrait or Landreath, meaning Church on the Sand.<ref name=\"CISI\"/> A stone Gothic Latin cross stands in the churchyard but nothing is known about its history.<ref>Langdon, A. G. (2002) ''Stone Crosses in Mid Cornwall''; 2nd ed. Federation of Old Cornwall Societies; p. 23</ref>\n\nUntil the 16th century the valley below St Blazey was an estuary of the [[River Par (UK)|River Par]] and the St Blazey was the lowest crossing point on the river. [[Mining in Cornwall and Devon|Tin mining]] up river caused the estuary to silt up and it had become marsh land by the early 19th century. The [[Par Canal]] was built by [[Joseph Treffry]] between 1829 and 1835; it forms part of the boundary with the parish of [[Tywardreath and Par]].<ref name=\"CISI\">{{cite web | url=http://www.historic-cornwall.org.uk/cisi/st_blazey/cisi_st_blazey_report.pdf | title=Cornwall Industrial Settlements Initiative, ST BLAZEY (with St Blazey Gate and West Par) | date=June 1999 | publisher = Historic Environment Service, Cornwall County Council | accessdate =4 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe town was once dominated by the local mining industries and their associated transport infrastructure. Historically copper and [[tin]] were mined in and around the parish, whilst more recently [[kaolinite|china clay]] has been the principal commodity mined. \"The Par & St Blazey Consols\" or \"South Prideaux Wood\" was a small tin mine just north of the town<ref>{{cite web| title=St. Austell Mining District \u2013 Par & St Blazey Consols| work=Cornwall in Focus| url=http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/blazeycons.php| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202165547/http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/blazeycons.php| archivedate=2 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Par Consols Mine]] lies to the south west.<ref>{{cite web| title=St. Austell Mining District \u2013 Par Consols Mine| work=Cornwall in Focus| url=http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/parcons.php| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202191931/http://www.cornwallinfocus.co.uk/history/parcons.php| archivedate=2 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The more extensive [[Fowey Consols mine]] lies to the east near [[Tywardreath]].\n\nThe port of [[Par Harbour]], which lies within the parish, was developed to ease the transport of these minerals, and initially connected to the mines by the [[Par Canal]]. Whilst the port of Par is within the parish, the village of [[Par, Cornwall|Par]] is actually just across the [[River Par (UK)|River Par]], and hence lies in the civil parish of Tywardreath.<ref name=\"osexp1\"/>\n\nThe Par Canal was soon replaced by the [[Cornwall Minerals Railway]], which had a depot and station in the town, and still exists as part of the [[Atlantic Coast Line, Cornwall|Atlantic Coast Line]]. Whilst [[St Blazey engine shed|St Blazey depot]] is still in use, [[St Blazey railway station|St Blazey station]] closed to passengers in 1925, and the town is now served by [[Par railway station|Par station]] on the [[Cornish Main Line]] in Par village.<ref name=\"osexp1\"/>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Eden Project geodesic domes panorama.jpg|thumb|360px|Panoramic view of the geodesic biome domes at the Eden Project]]\nThe [[Eden Project]] is located within the civil parish, and about a mile and half (2&nbsp;km) from the centre of the town. The large number of visitors this attracts has led to the development of tourism in the town. Other attractions, such as the [[Treffry Viaduct]] and the [[Luxulyan Valley]], are also close by, although actually within the adjoining parish of [[Luxulyan]].<ref name=\"osexp1\"/>\n\n==Education==\nPrimary education is provided by Biscovey Nursery and Infant Community School and Biscovey Junior School.\n\n==Sport==\nThe town's football team, [[St Blazey A.F.C.]], was the first club of England International goalkeeper [[Nigel Martyn]].\n\nThe town is also home to St Blazey Cricket Club which has two teams.\nThe cricket club is based at the top of Middleway Road.\n\n==Notable people==\nNotable people from the town include [[Edward Long]], the historian, who was born at Roselyon, in 1734, and educated at [[Liskeard]]. It is claimed by some as the birthplace of [[Ralph Allen]],<ref>{{cite web| title =Ralph Allen Biography| publisher =Bath Postal Museum| url =http://www.bathpostalmuseum.co.uk/explore/biographies/ralphallen.html| accessdate =17 September 2008| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090607024648/http://www.bathpostalmuseum.co.uk/explore/biographies/ralphallen.html| archivedate =7 June 2009| df =dmy-all}}</ref> notable architect of [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], although his christening took place at [[St Columb Major]]. [[John Rogers (divine)|John Rogers]], who supported the introduction of the [[man engine]] to Cornish mines, was curate here for a time.<ref name=\"dnb\">{{cite web | last = Marchant | first = E. C. | title = Rogers, John (1778\u20131856), divine, by E. C. Marchant | work = [[Dictionary of National Biography]] Vol. IL | publisher =[[Smith, Elder & Co.]] | year = 1897 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/olddnb.jsp?articleid=23988 | accessdate =13 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Charles Jeffries]], a [[Commissioner in The Salvation Army|Commissioner]] in [[The Salvation Army]], was posted to the town in 1883.\n\n==References==\n[[File:Disused Bible Christian Chapel - geograph.org.uk - 143541.jpg|Disused Methodist (formerly Bible Christian) chapel|thumb]]\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.stblaisetowncouncil.co.uk/ Town Council website]\n* [http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/Cornwall/StBlazey/index.html GENUKI website; St Blazey]\n* [http://crocat.cornwall.gov.uk/dserve/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=Overview.tcl&dsqSearch=(((text)='st%20blazey')AND(RefNo='*')) Cornwall Record Office Online Catalogue for St Blazey]\n<!-- REMOVED LINKS THAT FAIL [[WP:ELNO]] -->\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose 