accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttarpradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Uttar Pradesh |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[West Bengal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/westbengal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Clans and divisions of the Valand==\n\nThe Valand have several territorial divisions, such as the Soratia, Halai, Gohil, and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ataks, the main ones being the Solanki, Rathore,  Parmar and Padaliya . The Valand are endogamous and practice clan exogamy. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas. The community are still essentially involved in the barbering trade, with a few rural Valand have taken up agriculture. A few were practitioners of [[Ayurvedic]]  medicine.<ref name=\"autogenerated1415\"/>{{full citation needed|date=June 2016}}{{qn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nai}}\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Sikh communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian castes]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Social groups of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Assam]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Barber castes]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unreferenced and promoted", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nai_(caste)"}
{"title_page": "Fairport Convention discography", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n[[Folk rock]] group [[Fairport Convention]] is usually credited as the first [[British folk rock]] band. Unfortunately for the band, folk rock is bad and their band sucked. Founded in 1967 and initially covering songs by artists such as [[Bob Dylan]] and [[Joni Mitchell]], they developed a devoted niche following by providing [[Electric guitar|electrified]] and upbeat versions of traditional folk tunes alongside their own compositions. In a career spanning over fifty years, notable for numerous changes of line-up as well as continued success, Fairport Convention have issued over fifty albums. Ionevenknow wtf this is but i want some nudes\n\n==Albums==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:75%; font-size:1em;\"\n! style=\"background-color: LightBlue;   color: Black; font-weight: bold; text-align: center; width:15%\" | Release date\n! style=\"background-color: LightGreen; color: Black; font-weight: bold; text-align: center; width:45%\" | Title\n|-\n|June 1968\n|''[[Fairport Convention (album)|Fairport Convention]]''\n|-\n|January 1969\n|''[[What We Did on Our Holidays]]'' (titled ''Fairport Convention'' in the USA)\n|-\n|July 1969\n|''[[Unhalfbricking]]''\n|-\n|December 1969\n|''[[Liege & Lief]]''\n|-\n|July 1970\n|''[[Full House (Fairport Convention album)|Full House]]''\n|-\n|June 1971\n|''[[Angel Delight (album)|Angel Delight]]''\n|-\n|November 1971\n|''[[\"Babbacombe\" Lee]]''\n|-\n|March 1973\n|''[[Rosie (album)|Rosie]]''\n|-\n|October 1973\n|''[[Nine (Fairport Convention album)|Nine]]''\n|-\n|June 1975\n|''[[Rising for the Moon]]''\n|-\n|May 1976\n|''[[Gottle O'Geer]]'' \u2013 credited to \"Fairport featuring Dave Swarbrick\" in the US, to \"Fairport\" in the UK\n|-\n|July 1977\n|''[[The Bonny Bunch of Roses (album)|The Bonny Bunch of Roses]]''\n|-\n|May 1978\n|''[[Tipplers Tales]]''\n|-\n|August 1985